  "summary": "El Palmito (Lázaro Cárdenas) dam was at 21% on July 8, 2026, declining (inflows 44 m³/s vs releases 109 m³/s = net -0.19%/day), after falling from 25.9% on June 20 (~-0.27%/day). The July 23 outcome depends on whether the North American Monsoon engages mid-July to offset ongoing irrigation releases. Monte Carlo scenario-mixture over the 15-day horizon: continued mild drawdown (~18-19%, like dry 2024), rains offsetting (~20-21%), or strong recovery (~24%+, like 2025). Right-skewed with a small tropical-inflow tail. Median ~20%, P10 ~18.2, P90 ~23.2.",
  "reasoning": "My forecast for the El Palmito dam fill percentage on July 23, 2026:\n\n**Median: ~20.0%** (P10: 18.2%, P90: 23.2%)\n\n**Key reasoning:**\n- The reservoir stood at **21% on July 8, 2026** and was actively declining (inflows 44 m³/s vs releases 109 m³/s), after dropping from 25.9% on June 20.\n- Over the 15-day horizon to July 23, the outcome hinges on whether the North American Monsoon arrives to offset ongoing irrigation releases.\n- The distribution is right-skewed, capturing three scenarios: continued drawdown (~18-19%, resembling dry 2024), rains offsetting releases (~20-21%), and a strong monsoon recovery (~24%+, like 2025) — plus a thin tropical-inflow tail.\n- 2026's notably dry, \"crisis\"-framed season tilts weight toward the lower/central outcomes rather than a sharp recovery.\n\nThe premortem reviewer approved, confirming the center and spread match both the simulation and independent reasoning.",
